  "summary": "This chunk contains detailed excerpts from the Munich Handbook (CLM 849), including four major necromantic rituals: a nautical spirit-transport rite, horse conjuration (No. 9), resurrection of the dead (No. 10), invisibility (No. 11), and love magic (No. 12). It lists specific spirit names—Fyron, Dyspil, Onoroy, Sysabel, Cotroy, Tyroy, Rimel, Orooth; Lautrayth/Feremin/Oliroomim; Brimer/Suburith/Tranauit/Lyroth/Beryen/Damayn; Fyriel/Mememil/Berith/Taraor; and Belial/Astaroth/Paymon—and describes their invocation via protective circles, ritual tools (sword, bridle, golden ring), and ingredients (blessed water, incense, virgin wax). The rituals blend Christian invocations with demonic evocation, reflecting the hybrid theological logic of medieval magical practice.",
  "key_passages": [
    "hoc circulo, ego invoco vos per vestram subieccionem michi factam, vt statim sine mora subito et incontinenti hincp debeatis accedere...",
    "O Lautrayth, Feremin, [et] Oliroomim, spiritus peccatoribus insistentes, ego... vos coniuro per illum qui dixit et facta sunt...",
    "Coniuro vos, omnes demones scriptos in hoc anulo – quem in manibus habeas, per Patrem et Filium et Spiritum Sanctum...",
    "Ego, talis, coniuro vos, O Fyriel, Mememil, Berith, [et] Taraor, spiritus potentes... per vnicam, inseparabilem, ac indiuiduam trinitatem...",
    "Tu Belial, tu Astarotht, tu Paymon, ad hoc sitis opus michi adiutores."
  ]
}